This article is a presidential proclamation issued by Barack Obama on December 31, 2012, commemorating the 150th anniversary of the Emancipation Proclamation. The proclamation highlights the significance of the Emancipation Proclamation, which was issued by President Abraham Lincoln on January 1, 1863, during the American Civil War. It acknowledges the divisions and conflicts of the time, with brother fighting against brother and sister against sister. The proclamation also emphasizes the hope and light that persisted, as well as the courage of President Lincoln in declaring that all persons held as slaves in rebellious areas shall be forever free. It recognizes the efforts made by Lincoln to empower African Americans and unite the nation in freedom and equality. The proclamation calls on Americans to observe the 150th anniversary with appropriate programs and activities that celebrate and reaffirm the principles of the Emancipation Proclamation.